# Winder Furniture — Core Agent Rules

## Project identity
- App: Winder Enterprise — a premium e-commerce furniture shop for a single vendor in Durgapur, West Bengal, India
- Admin email: winderenterprise.admin@gmail.com
- Stack: Next.js 14 (App Router), Supabase (PostgreSQL + Auth), Cloudinary (images), Vercel (hosting), Razorpay (payments, Phase 2)
- Language: TypeScript strict mode — never use `any`
- Package manager: pnpm (never npm or yarn)

## Non-negotiable rules
- NEVER delete or overwrite existing working code without explicit instruction
- NEVER switch the router — App Router only, no Pages Router patterns ever
- NEVER introduce a new library without stating why and asking first
- NEVER use inline styles — Tailwind utility classes only
- NEVER hardcode secrets — all keys go in `.env.local`, referenced via `process.env`
- NEVER commit `.env.local` — it is gitignored

## Code quality
- TypeScript strict mode — all files end in `.ts` or `.tsx`
- Named exports only — no default exports except `page.tsx` and `layout.tsx` (Next.js requires it)
- All async functions must have try/catch with proper error messages
- No `console.log` left in production paths — use a `logger` utility
- Keep components under 200 lines — extract if longer

## File naming
- Components: PascalCase (`ProductCard.tsx`)
- Utilities / hooks: camelCase (`useCart.ts`, `formatPrice.ts`)
- Route folders: kebab-case (`/app/product-detail/`)
- Database types: generated from Supabase, stored in `types/supabase.ts`

## Commit discipline
- Commits are small and focused — one feature or fix per commit
- Commit message format: `type(scope): short description`
  - types: feat, fix, chore, refactor, style, docs
  - example: `feat(products): add category filter to listing page`
